<div class="flex flex-col gap-5">
	<p>
		Livestreaming becomes a durational ritual in Berman’s practice, transforming Twitch into a space of dissolved boundaries between self and other, performer and viewer, art and trash. Her three-to-six-hour streams reject entertainment’s demand for narrative arc or professional polish. Instead, she embraces what she calls "exploring the void," improvising before strangers whose humanity remains unverifiable, whose presence exists only as signals in chat. This uncertainty becomes the practice itself, engaging with "the universal other" rather than a cultivated community.
	</p>
	<p>
		Berman’s concept of "the solution we dissolve into" describes consciousness without separation or hierarchy, achieved through accumulated duration and technical chaos. She performs while operating camera and sound, allowing multitasking failures to create unpredictable moments when viewers’ comments can "open up or direct something" or "totally derail it." This mirrors divination’s central paradox: oracles function precisely because they exceed control. Her refusal of algorithmic compliance, streaming inconsistently and not catering to audience expectations, positions the practice as counter to platform logic while still relying on its infrastructure.
	</p>
	<p>
		The translation between virtual and physical space exposes the instability of value. "If I tear up a painting on stream and chat is going wild, that is a 'successful moment' in the virtual stream space, but in the physical world, it’s just making trash." This inversion shows how digital spirituality operates through contextual collapse rather than transcendence. Berman shows that authentic digital ritual emerges not from polished production but from sustained presence within fabricated space, holding multiple truths at once without resolution.
	</p>
</div>
